There's a few things in that.
Functions can access variables of outer scopes. Even if the function that scope belongs to has returned, they retain a connection to the variable, and not its value at function definition time.
`var` variables have function scope. No matter where in a function it's declared, it is valid for the whole function.
`let` variables are block scope, they exist only within the scope (and there's the TDZ, but that's another topic). `let` in `for` loops is a bit special, though: It's rebound per iteration, initialized to the value of the previous variable. So a function expression within the loop will have its own private variable that will not be changed in further iterations.

About the same could be achieved using IIFEs (Immediately Invoked Function Expressions), you will find them especially in a lot of pre-ES6 code.

The `*` means different things depending on the context.  When used as part of a variable declaration, it indicates a pointer type.  ```C
 //declare a variable called num of type "pointer to integer"
int *num;  
//declare a variable called value of type "pointer to float"
float *value;
```   Those pointer variables as declared currently hold garbage values.  So we give them a value of either NULL (a special pointer value) or the address of the int/float that want to hold. ```C
// declare a variable of type integer and set it to 5
int a = 5;
// declare a variable of type 'pointer to integer' and set its value to the address of the int a
int *ptr_to_a = &a;```
When used with the variable itself (not as part of a declaration), it is called the "dereference operator".  Dereferencing means "go to the address stored in the pointer variable and give me the value stored there"  ```C
// dereference the ptr_to_a pointer and print the value there.
printf("a is %i\n", *ptr_to_a);   // will print 5```

```C
// show that a is still 5 as well
printf("a is %i\n", a);  // will print 5
// change the value stored in the variable a
*ptr_to_a = 10;
printf("a is now %i\n", a);  // will print 10```

